{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17594569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17594569"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:49:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:49:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15326"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15326"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.11,0.26,0.53,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8017"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69322"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8017"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15326"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54775"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8755"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19481"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19483"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69322","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69322"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory tests can assess various aspects of liver function, including its synthetic capacity.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following patterns of albumin and International Normalised Ratio (INR) indicates impaired liver synthetic function?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Elevated albumin and elevated INR","Low albumin and low INR","Elevated albumin and low INR","Low albumin and elevated INR","Normal albumin and elevated INR"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe liver synthesises many essential proteins including albumin and coagulation factors. When hepatic synthetic function is impaired, both production of albumin and clotting factors decreases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pattern combinations can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElevated albumin and elevated INR\u003C/strong\u003E - Physiologically impossible as these move in opposite directions with liver dysfunction\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow albumin and low INR\u003C/strong\u003E - Not consistent with liver dysfunction as INR rises when clotting factors are reduced\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElevated albumin and low INR\u003C/strong\u003E - Not seen in liver disease as albumin production decreases with dysfunction\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow albumin and elevated INR\u003C/strong\u003E - Correct pattern indicating reduced synthetic function:\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDecreased albumin synthesis leads to low serum levels\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDecreased clotting factor production leads to prolonged clotting times and elevated INR\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal albumin and elevated INR\u003C/strong\u003E - May occur with vitamin K deficiency but does not indicate true synthetic dysfunction\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlbumin has a long half-life of about 20 days, while clotting factors have much shorter half-lives of hours to days. Therefore, an elevated INR may be an earlier indicator of acute liver dysfunction than albumin levels.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The liver synthesises both albumin and clotting factors; reduced synthetic function results in low albumin and elevated INR.","Albumin has a long half-life (20 days) while clotting factors have short half-lives (hours), making them sensitive indicators of acute liver dysfunction.","Combined low albumin and elevated INR is specific for impaired hepatic synthetic function."],"references":["Joseph A, Samant H. Jaundice. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31334972","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Gasmi B, Kleiner DE. Liver Histology: Diagnostic and Prognostic Features. Clin Liver Dis. 2020 Feb;24(1):61-74. doi: 10.1016/j.cld.2019.09.004. Epub 2019 Oct 31. PMID: 31753251; PMCID: PMC6986808"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54775"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15326"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54775"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T19:33:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T19:34:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8017"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69322"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6